    <body.head>
      <hedline>
        <hl1>In Jail for Drugs</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Wade Stone letter backs strict prison sentencing guidelines for those convicted of trafficking in large quantities of cocaine or heroin (May 12 editorial)</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''New York's Harmful Drug Laws'' (editorial, May 12): You make a plea for reform of the state's strict drug laws and mandatory sentencing structure.</p>
        <p>People caught with large quantities of cocaine or heroin or in the act of selling these drugs are not simply victims of a powerful addiction; they deserve no breaks from the strict current measures.</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''New York's Harmful Drug Laws'' (editorial, May 12): You make a plea for reform of the state's strict drug laws and mandatory sentencing structure.</p>
        <p>People caught with large quantities of cocaine or heroin or in the act of selling these drugs are not simply victims of a powerful addiction; they deserve no breaks from the strict current measures.</p>
        <p>What you do not say in your editorial is that the great improvement in the quality of life in New York City between 1980 and 1999 coincides with the increase in imprisonment of drug dealers. Perhaps the price for a safer, more livable city amounts to the high costs necessary to keep those who choose to deal drugs off our streets.</p>
        <p>WADE STONE  New York, May 12, 2000</p>
      </block>
